---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="N+1 Queries Problem - FraiseQL Solution"
  description="How FraiseQL eliminates N+1 query problems through compile-time optimization."
>
  <div style="padding: 2rem; max-width: 1280px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h1>⚠️ Problem: N+1 Queries</h1>
    <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; color: #666;">
      <strong>How compile-time optimization makes N+1 queries impossible</strong>
    </p>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>What is the N+1 Query Problem?</h2>

      <p>
        When fetching related data, resolvers inadvertently load data inefficiently:
      </p>

      <pre><code>{`// Resolver for getting users
const users = await db.query("SELECT * FROM users LIMIT 10");
// Result: 1 query ✓

// For EACH user, fetch their posts
for (const user of users) {
  user.posts = await db.query("SELECT * FROM posts WHERE user_id = \$1", [user.id]);
}
// Result: 10 queries ✗

// For EACH post, fetch its comments
for (const post of user.posts) {
  post.comments = await db.query("SELECT * FROM comments WHERE post_id = \$1", [post.id]);
}
// Result: 10 × 50 = 500 queries ✗

// Total: 1 + 10 + 500 = 511 queries instead of 1!`}</code></pre>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #c41c3b;">
        <strong>Called "N+1" because:</strong> 1 query for parent, then N queries for each child, then N×M queries for grandchildren.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Why N+1 Happens</h2>

      <p>
        GraphQL's resolver chain architecture makes it easy to trigger N+1:
      </p>

      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>Resolver per field:</strong> Each field has its own resolver function
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Independent execution:</strong> Resolvers don't know about sibling resolvers
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>No visibility:</strong> Can't see the entire query at once (no query introspection)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Easy to miss:</strong> Developers often don't realize they've created N+1
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #666;">
        <em>Result: Slow performance that's hard to debug and often hidden until production.</em>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Real-World Impact</h2>

      <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0;">
        <tr style="background: #f5f3ff;">
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: left; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Query Pattern</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Expected Queries</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Actual Queries (N+1)</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Latency Increase</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Get 10 users with posts</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">1</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">11</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">10-50×</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Get 10 users → posts → comments</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">1</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">511</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">100-500×</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Get 100 products with variants and inventory</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">1</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">10,100</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">1000-5000×</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Common Solutions (Before FraiseQL)</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">1. DataLoader (Partial Solution)</h3>
      <p>
        Batch queries together in the same tick:
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`// With DataLoader
const userLoader = new DataLoader(async (userIds) => {
  // Batched: SELECT * FROM users WHERE id IN (...)
  return db.query("SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ANY(\$1)", [userIds]);
});

// Still N+1 for second level!
for (const user of users) {
  user.posts = await postLoader.load(user.id);  // DataLoader batches these
}

for (const post of user.posts) {
  post.comments = await commentLoader.load(post.id);  // Still N+1 here!
}

// Result: Better, but doesn't solve nested N+1 problems`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">2. Query Hints (Manual Optimization)</h3>
      <p>
        Developers manually optimize queries:
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`// Developer adds @traceQuery hint
const users = await db.query("""
  SELECT users.*, posts.*, comments.*
  FROM users
  LEFT JOIN posts ON users.id = posts.user_id
  LEFT JOIN comments ON posts.id = comments.post_id
  WHERE users.id IN (...)
""");

// Result: Works, but requires developers to manually write SQL
// Fragile: Easy to break with field additions
// Not scalable: Every query needs manual optimization`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">3. Redis Caching (Works Around Problem)</h3>
      <p>
        Cache expensive queries:
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`// Cache user + posts + comments
const cached = await redis.get("user:123");
if (!cached) {
  // Fetch all three
  cached = await fetchUserWithPostsAndComments(123);
  await redis.set("user:123", cached, { EX: 3600 });
}
return cached;

// Result: Works, but:
// - Cache invalidation is hard
// - Memory overhead
// - Stale data issues
// - Doesn't solve the problem, just hides it`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>FraiseQL Solution: Compile-Time Optimization</h2>

      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL prevents N+1 queries at compile time.</strong> The compiler analyzes your query structure and generates optimized SQL:
      </p>

      <pre><code>{`# Query for users with posts and comments
query GetUsersWithPosts {
  users {
    id
    name
    posts {
      id
      title
      comments {
        id
        text
      }
    }
  }
}

# At compile time, FraiseQL:
# 1. Analyzes nested structure: users → posts → comments
# 2. Recognizes joins needed
# 3. Generates single optimized SQL:

SELECT
  u.id as user_id, u.name,
  p.id as post_id, p.title,
  c.id as comment_id, c.text
FROM users u
LEFT JOIN posts p ON u.id = p.user_id
LEFT JOIN comments c ON p.id = c.post_id
ORDER BY u.id, p.id, c.id;

# At runtime:
# - Execute single pre-compiled query
# - PostgreSQL optimizer chooses best join strategy
# - Result: 1 query instead of 1 + N + N×M`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">How FraiseQL Prevents N+1</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Compiler sees entire query:</strong> Not just individual fields, but complete structure
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Pre-optimization:</strong> SQL is generated before runtime, with all joins planned
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Single SQL execution:</strong> No resolver chains that could trigger sequential queries
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Tested safeguards:</strong> Comprehensive tests verify efficient query plans
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Performance Comparison</h2>

      <pre><code>{`Scenario: Fetch 100 users with 50 posts each and 10 comments per post

Traditional GraphQL (N+1):
- Initial query: 1 (get 100 users)
- Posts queries: 100 (one per user)
- Comments queries: 5,000 (one per post)
- Total: 5,101 queries
- Latency: 50-100 seconds
- Database CPU: Maxed out

With DataLoader:
- Batched queries: ~3 batches
- Total: 103 queries
- Latency: 5-10 seconds
- Still slow, still problematic

With FraiseQL:
- Single compiled query: 1
- Latency: 50-100ms
- Database CPU: &lt;1%
- 100-1000× faster`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Key Takeaway</h2>

      <p style="padding: 1rem; background: #f0fdf4; border-left: 4px solid #059669; border-radius: 4px;">
        <strong>FraiseQL addresses N+1 at compile time.</strong> Rather than relying on runtime optimizations like DataLoader or caching, the compiler analyzes your entire query structure and generates a single optimized SQL statement with all joins pre-planned.
      </p>
    </section>

